{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8a72e2ff-2a90-439a-82d8-3cbcd9810a87","content":"## What happened\n\n**macOS's native crypto library (Apple Security.framework) does not support DSA.** In .NET 11, the OpenSSL fallback that previously enabled DSA on macOS was removed, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on that platform. Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) still support it.\n\n## How to fix\n\n**Short-term** — use a managed, cross-platform DSA implementation via **BouncyCastle**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n**Long-term** — migrate off DSA entirely. DSA is a legacy algorithm (FIPS 186-5 deprecated it in 2023). Prefer **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, both of which are natively supported on all three platforms in .NET.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b676ac4b-8f34-481a-8acf-dcc8d571d9d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, and then further in later versions, .NET has been deprecating and removing certain cryptographic algorithms that are considered legacy/insecure. \n\nSpecifically, DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) support on macOS has been affected because:\n\n1. macOS's native crypto library (Apple's CryptoKit/Security framework) does not support DSA.\n\n\n2. In earlier .NET versions, DSA on macOS relied on OpenSSL as a fallback, but Microsoft has progressively removed that support for legacy algorithms.\n3. The breaking change occurred in .NET 7+, where `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS since Apple's security frameworks don't support DSA and .NET no longer uses OpenSSL as a workaround.\n\nI'm trying to recall the exact timeline here—the user mentions upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, and given the current date is May 2026, that would be a recent upgrade. On macOS, DSA was never natively supported by Apple's frameworks, and while .NET used to rely on OpenSSL for unsupported algorithms, that support was eventually removed. DSA.Create() has been throwing PlatformNotSupportedException on macOS for a long time in .NET Core and beyond, though workarounds existed if you had OpenSSL installed via Homebrew. I need to think through the actual timeline of when this behavior changed and whether there's something specific happening between .NET 10 and .NET 11. on macOS because Apple's Security framework doesn't include DSA support. So the real issue is that DSA.Create() throws PlatformNotSupportedException on macOS, and the workaround would be to either use a managed implementation like BouncyCastle or migrate away from DSA since it's considered legacy anyway. DSA support was removed in .NET 11 on macOS because Apple's Security framework doesn't support it, and the OpenSSL fallback that existed in .NET 10 has been stripped out. To work around this, I should either migrate to ECDSA or Ed25519, use BouncyCastle as a managed cross-platform alternative, or directly P/Invoke to OpenSSL if it's available on the system.","outputTokens":1894,"requestId":"886B:A067E:1D4C59D:20BDBEA:69FA9CD0"},"id":"7585ecba-09d6-43fa-a078-311a2f9f2097","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:44:24.322Z","parentId":"0c9bd6f2-51b9-46d1-82a3-d59eff44e535"}
